{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514800"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:26:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:26:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12384"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12384"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.29,0.02,0.47,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4894"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77812"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4894"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12384"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63333"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"489"},{"type":"tags","id":"1418"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"},{"type":"tags","id":"4875"},{"type":"tags","id":"6610"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7954"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39229"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77812"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman who just returned from the United States presents to the Emergency Department complaining of weakness of her right arm. On examination, it is evident that her speech is slurred. Her right arm power is 3/5. There is loss of the nasolabial fold on the right side when she smiles, but she is still able to shut both her eyes. Her lower limb neurological examination is normal, except for a swollen left leg up to knee level that is warm and tender to touch. Her blood pressure is 165/90 mmHg, pulse 90/min with regular rhythm, respiratory rate 16/min, temperature 37.4\u00b0C, oxygen saturation 98% on room air. She does not have shortness of breath and her respiratory examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVenous ultrasound reveals a thrombus in one of the deep veins in her lower leg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most likely to reveal the source of her neurological event?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT pulmonary angiogram","Carotid ultrasound scan","Blood cultures","Trans-oesophageal echocardiogram","Ventilation-perfusion scan"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is most likely to have an embolic stroke - due to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eparadoxical embolism \u003C/strong\u003Esecondary to her recent deep vein thrombosis. Paradoxical embolism occurs when there is a right-to-left shunt (i.e., patent foramen ovale or atrial septal defect) that causes the venous embolus to bypass the pulmonary circulation and enter the systemic circulation, thereby resulting in various arterial occlusion events - in this case, stroke. Paradoxical embolism accounts for a very small percentage of arterial emboli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo identify the source of her stroke, \u003Cstrong\u003Etrans-oesophageal echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be the most appropriate option to look for any defect in her heart that is causing the right-to-left shunt. In this case, the cause is most likely patent foramen ovale (PFO), which is often asymptomatic and not known to the person unless it is causing health event. In those with suspected PFO, a bubble echocardiogram could be done to determine the presence of PFO.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eventilation-perfusion scan\u003C/strong\u003E could be useful to rule out potential pulmonary embolism resulting from her deep vein thrombosis, it would not help in identifying the cause of her stroke. Besides, she does not complain of dyspnoea and her respiratory examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotid ultrasound scan\u003C/strong\u003E is helpful in identifying the cause of embolus in patients with stroke suspected to have a carotid plaque giving off emboli. However, given the patient\u0027s young age and the clinical and radiological evidence of deep vein thrombosis, this is less likely the cause of her stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMultiple \u003Cstrong\u003Eblood cultures \u003C/strong\u003Eare usually ordered to look for infective endocarditis, which could potentially cause infectious emboli. In this case, there is no history of fever and no murmur mentioned on examination. Also the finding of deep vein thrombosis goes more in favour of paradoxical embolism rather than bacterial endocarditis, so blood cultures would not be of the first priority in this case. Nevertheless, having said that, congenital heart defects also predispose to infective endocarditis, so further investigations should be done to completely rule out the possibility of infective endocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Paradoxical embolism refers to an embolus that is carried from the venous circulation to arterial circulation, or vice versa. It accounts for only 2% of arterial emboli.","Trans-oesophageal echocardiogram is a key investigation to identify cardiac sources of emboli, such as a patent foramen ovale, in cases of paradoxical embolism."],"references":["Hakman EN \u0026 Cowling KM. Paradoxical embolism [Internet]. The United States: StatPearls Publishing LLC; 2015 [updated 2022 Sep 05; cited 2023 Jan 13]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470196/","Rosenberger P, Shernan SK, Body SC, Eltzschig HK. Utility of intraoperative transesophageal echocardiography for diagnosis of pulmonary embolism. Anesth Analg. 2004 Jul;99(1):12-16. doi: 10.1213/01.ANE.0000117284.25696.64. PMID: 15281493. Avaialble from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15281493/","Palazzuoli A, Ricci D, Lenzi C, Lenzi J, Palazzuoli V. Transesophageal echocardiography for identifying potential cardiac sources of embolism in patients with stroke. Neurol Sci. 2000 Aug;21(4):195-202. doi: 10.1007/s100720070076. PMID: 11214657. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11214657/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63333"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12384"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63333"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T12:38:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T12:39:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4894"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77812"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"da